http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#com.@value: Transient data (e.g., variable) of the type boolean.
Transient data (e.g., variable) of the type file.
Transient data (e.g., variable) of the type list.
Transient data (e.g., variable) of the type string.
Appends text to a file.
AutomationOperations are the most prominent type of RPA operations. They access external data, operate on applications, call services, or automate aspects of the operating system.
An application to open and navigate web pages.
Simulates the click on a button.
Simulates a click on specific coordinates on the screen.
Transient data of more complex types, such as tabular data.
Splits the control flow in concurrently executable branches.

Controlflow Operations are responsible for steering the sequence of operations within the bot and include, for example, elements to making decisions and thus splitting the control flow, or triggers that wait for external events.
Creates a new file.
Represents the creation of a new data resource.
Data operations access CSO:Data and differ in whether data is read, written, transformed, or whether the file itself is manipulated.
Data resources exist independently of a software artifact or RPA bot, such as files on a hard drive, databases, websites and so on. They may be created, accessed and modified by software and bots.
Splits the control flow in alternative branches.
Deletes a file.
A software to send and receive emails.
Exports a file, usually in a different format and without saving the actual file used for export.
Files are data that are not executable.
Enteres text in a input text box.
Retrieves the value of an attribute of an element.
Retrieves a list of emails from a specified account.
Retrieves a list of emails from a specified account.
Extracts text from files or elements.

Human Interface Operations are usually independent of concrete software and data. They simulate the input of a human user, using mouse clicks and keystrokes, for example. Sometimes computer vision capabilities are used to locate the user interface element in question.
Sets the text value of a certain element.
Internal Operations do not access any data or software outside the bot. They are used to operate on internal variables, e.g., for manipulating bot-internal variables.
Opens a given file.
Simulates the press of a key.
Reads the value of a cell in a spreadsheet.
Text that is formatted.
A step in a RPA context container's cleanup sequence.

Context containers provide an environment so that certain operations can be performed properly. The container may contain set-up and clean-up steps, e.g., to start an application and open a file, and to save and close after the operation(s) have been executed.
A step in a RPA context container's setup sequence.
A single step in an RPA context container.
RPAOperations are CSO:ComputationalTasks and represent the smallest building blocks of RPA Bots.
Saves the file.
Selects a checkbox.
Selects an item from a list.
Selects items from a list.
Sends an email.
Transient data of primitive data types, strings, numbers etc.
Terminates the current instance of the software.
Software Control Operations manage software in more general, independent of data. They do not access data, but, for example, can start and stop applications.
Starts a new instance of the software.
Data stored in tabular form.
A software for organizing data in tabular form.
A plain text document.
Transient data represents volatile data, such as variables, that only exist within the local scope of a software artifact or an RPA bot. Such data is lost when the software/bot instance terminates.
Operations that manipulate transient data (i.e., variables) internally
A software to create formatted text documents.
Writes a value to a cell in a spreadsheet.
